---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import computerTurtle from "../images/computerTurtle.webp";
---

<BaseLayout title="john's computer">
  <main class="page-container">
    <section class="page-text">
      <p>
        Now, imagine you’re out there on a bright and crisp fall afternoon,
        watching your son run down the football field, zigzaggin' past the other
        fellas, just like a pro. Now, think of a computer as his playbook. You
        know how the playbook has got all them strategies, plans, and formations
        drawn out detail by detail, helping him to make the right moves on the
        field? Well, a computer is like that playbook but for almost anything
        you can think of in the modern world.
      </p>

      <p>
        A computer’s got this here brain called a central processin' unit, or
        CPU for short, that works quicker than a hiccup. It's kind of like your
        son, always thinkin' several steps ahead, plottin' out the best path
        forward, makin' rapid-fire decisions in the blink of an eye.
      </p>

      <p>
        But now, a computer ain’t just all about speed. It's also got memory,
        kinda like how you remember all your daughter's volleyball plays and
        your son’s football achievements. This memory stores all sorts of
        important things, keepin' track of the data, so it can use it later on
        when it needs it. It has two types of memory: one that remembers things
        even when it’s turned off, like you remember the old days, and another
        that forgets everything once it's shut down, a bit like forgettin' a bad
        play and moving on to the next one.
      </p>

      <p>
        Now picture your daughter playin' volleyball, she's got that there
        network of teammates, always communicatin', passin' the ball back and
        forth, workin' together like a well-oiled machine. A computer’s got
        somethin' similar, a network that allows it to communicate with other
        computers all over the world, sharin' information, just like how the
        team shares the ball, workin' together to achieve a common goal.
      </p>
      <p>
        And don’t forget the monitor, that’s like the scoreboard at the games,
        showing you all the important info clear as day, keepin' you updated on
        what's happenin' at every moment.
      </p>
      <p>
        So there you have it. A computer is like a combination of a playbook, a
        super-fast decision maker like your son, a memory keeper like you, and a
        teamwork facilitator like your daughter’s volleyball team, all rolled
        into one fine piece of machinery, helping folks to work, learn, and stay
        connected in this fast-paced world we're living in.
      </p>

      <p>
        Now, you remember I mentioned the CPU, which is the brain of the
        operation, right? Well, this thing can process a sheer mountain of
        calculations and decisions in a split second, sort of like how your son
        has that keen eye on the field, picking out the best paths and makin'
        split-second decisions that can turn the tide of the game. And as he
        grew, he just got better and better, understandin' the nuances of the
        game, same as a computer with a newer, more powerful CPU can do more
        complex tasks faster than you can say "touchdown."
      </p>
      <p>
        Now speakin' of memory, it holds onto a treasure trove of information.
        We've got one kind called RAM; it's like the immediate thoughts in your
        head, it holds onto the most recent stuff, making it quick and easy to
        access. Now, your son's journey through life, from scurrying as a little
        tyke on the family farm to becoming a running back star in high school,
        is kind of stored in a memory space like a hard drive, where all the
        long-term memories and experiences are kept, built layer upon layer,
        enriching and informin' his path as he stepped boldly into the world,
        developin' a strong sense for social justice, ready to make a change in
        the world with all that wisdom he's amassed over the years.
      </p>
      <p>
        And remember the networkin' part? Well, in the big wide world of
        computers, there's this amazing network called the internet that
        connects computers far and wide, allowin' them to share information
        across vast distances in the blink of an eye. It's kinda like when your
        son went off to college, broadening his horizons, meetin' new people,
        learnin' new things, and forming connections that span across states,
        bringin' together a wealth of knowledge and perspectives, just like how
        computers can pull information from all over the world.
      </p>
      <p>
        As for the monitor, it's the window into the soul of the computer,
        givin' you a clear view of everything that's happening inside that
        machine, showcasing a world of knowledge, entertainment, and
        connections, like a living testament to your son's ever-evolving journey
        through life, highlighting his accomplishments and showcassin' the depth
        of his experiences.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now, throughout all these details about your son, I reckon we haven't
        forgotten your daughter, still steadfastly playing volleyball, holding
        her ground, and bein' an important part of the family, keeping up the
        spirit and embodyin' the joy of the game, though we ain't goin' in
        details about her journey today.
      </p>
    </section>
    <div class="page-image">
      <Image
        src={computerTurtle}
        alt="A self-portrait of John"
        class="page-image-img"
      />
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
